I also have ptsd and this has helped me to relax and concentrate on what's important to me.  I have always put others first and never took time for myself even though everyone has told me to. I have found that the time that i have spent doing yoga had helped a lot in many ways. I go to the Hindu temple and a lot of times my back would get to hurting so i would have to stop and try to refocus because of the pain in my lower back but now i can stay without any distractions.  My mom has also been doing part of the  techniques and it has also helped her. She spent 23 days in the hospital most of which was in the icu. When she came home she couldn't walk. What a beautiful practice with an unexpected gift.  I have always had an ambivalent relationship with power, including my own personal, internal power (one of the effects of trauma).  As I've journeyed through these 30 days of "dedicate," I arrived on the mat today and found myself immediately releasing my resistance to my own power.  Lo and behold, the gift:  I flowed through this practice with ease, grace and gentleness!  Not to be confused with "perfection of form" (whatever that might mean).  But rather, in somehow finally fully opening to and allowing my power, I also touched grace and gentleness.  They were/are interconnected.  . . .  The embodied experience --after many years of patience, perseverance, trust and determined healing work with bucketfuls of grief and tears--of a line in a song that came to/through me one day, "There's a strong yet gentle woman waiting to be born if I can find a way to make it through this last long night."        . . . . Trusting the process; being dedicated; believing in the transformative power of love, and, one day, we experience in our body in a way that words cannot do justice that the armor of being a "survivor" has shattered and fallen away and we have found our deeper self who was there waiting for us:  for me, the strong yet gentle woman and the deepest feeling of peace I have yet experienced.  My hallelujah moment.  Gratitude and love to Adrienne and to all of us on our individual journeys together.
